    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u explain the maillard reaction to me? specifically what's happening chemically and what temperature ranges do i need to hit for it to really start happening in bread crusts?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a non-enzymatic browning reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that occurs when food is heated, resulting in the formation of new flavor compounds and browns color pigments. During bread crust browning, the Maillard reaction occurs when the yeast fermentation process and the Maillard reaction overlap, typically between 140°C to 180°C (284°F to 356°F). For significant crust browning, temperatures around 160°C to 180°C (320°F to 356°F) are ideal, allowing the Maillard reaction to reach its peak.",
