    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i want to get more of that flavor, should i be looking at adding more sugar to the dough or is it more about how the heat is applied to the surface?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Adding more sugar will not necessarily enhance the Maillard reaction, as the reaction is primarily driven by the amino acids and reducing sugars being in close proximity, not necessarily their quantity. However, having a dough with a higher moisture content, often achieved by using more yeast or a preferment, can help to break down starches and create more reducing sugars, which can then react with amino acids during baking to produce more Maillard reaction products. So, it's more about the conditions and application of heat that matter.",
      "source": "target",
